    <section id="section-1">
      <h2>1. What lead generation software actually does</h2>

      <p>Lead generation software is a broad label applied to tools that solve very different problems. Before buying anything, it helps to understand the two fundamental jobs in lead generation and which software category addresses each.</p>

      <p><strong>Job 1 — Attract.</strong> Someone who does not know you exist needs to encounter your offer. This requires a traffic source: organic content that ranks in search, social media where you engage your target audience, paid advertising that places your offer in front of targeted people, or someone else's email list (solo ads, joint ventures). Software in this category includes Facebook prospecting tools, traffic rotators, and ad management platforms.</p>

      <p><strong>Job 2 — Capture.</strong> A visitor who arrives at your offer needs a mechanism that converts their interest into a lasting connection — typically by exchanging their email address for something valuable. Software in this category includes landing page builders, email opt-in form tools, and the email marketing platforms that store and manage your subscriber list.</p>

      <p><strong>Job 3 — Nurture.</strong> A new subscriber is not a buyer. They need a sequence of follow-up communications that build trust, deliver value, and present your offer at the right moment. This is handled by email marketing automation — autoresponders, sequences, and segmentation tools.</p>

      <p>Most "lead generation software" reviews conflate all three jobs under one label, which is why the recommendations look so different depending on where you read. The tool that helps you find prospects on Facebook (Job 1) is a fundamentally different product from the email platform that follows up with them automatically (Job 3). Knowing which job you are solving right now is the first step to buying the right tool.</p>

      <div class="callout info">
        <strong>Which job should beginners solve first?</strong> Capture (Job 2). Before spending on traffic tools, you need a landing page and an email list to send traffic to. Setting up a free email marketing account and a simple capture page costs nothing and takes an afternoon. Buying traffic to send to a page that does not exist yet is how beginners burn their first budget.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="section-2">
      <h2>2. The three software categories</h2>

      <p>With the two-job framework above, the full lead generation software landscape resolves into three distinct categories. Most online business builders need at least one tool from each.</p>

      <div class="table-scroll">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
